data.content:
**MSTest Collection Assertions**

Your test works but produces unhelpful failure messages (just "Assert.IsTrue failed"). MSTest provides `CollectionAssert` and modern `Assert` methods with much better diagnostics:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    // Assert exact count — failure message shows actual vs expected
    Assert.AreEqual(3, users.Count);

    // Assert all satisfy a condition
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive), "Expected all users to be active");

    // Assert a specific item exists
    Assert.IsTrue(users.Any(u => u.Role == "Admin"), "Expected an Admin user");
}
```

**Key improvements:**

| Instead of | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count > 0)` | `Assert.AreNotEqual(0, x.Count)` | Shows actual count on failure |
| `Assert.IsTrue(x.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.AreEqual(3, x.Count)` | Shows "Expected 3, got 5" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(obj != null)` | `Assert.IsNotNull(obj)` | Clearer intent + message |
| `Assert.IsTrue(condition)` | Add a message parameter | `"Expected all users active"` |

**Other `CollectionAssert` helpers:**

```csharp
// Verify a collection contains a specific element
CollectionAssert.Contains(users, expectedUser);

// Verify two collections have the same elements (order-sensitive)
CollectionAssert.AreEqual(expected, actual);

// Same elements, any order
CollectionAssert.AreEquivalent(expected, actual);

// All elements are of a given type
CollectionAssert.AllAreSatisfied(users, u => Assert.IsTrue(u.IsActive));
```

The general rule: **avoid bare `Assert.IsTrue`** — use the most specific assert available so failures tell you *what* went wrong.
